################################################################################
#                                                                              #
#                    Splunk on Splunk Add-on (S.o.S Add-on)                    #
#                             for Unix and Linux                               #
#             A collection of inputs for the Splunk on Splunk app              #
#                                                                              #
################################################################################

The Splunk on Splunk Add-on is a collection of inputs for the Splunk on Splunk 
app. It contains the following scripted inputs:

  ps_sos.sh
  Gathers memory and CPU statistics for Splunk Web, splunkd, and search 
  processes.

  lsof_sos.sh
  Gathers file descriptor usage for splunkd and Splunk Web.

The instance of the Splunk on Splunk app installed on your search head uses the
information gathered from these scripts to populate views for analysis of
resource usage in your Splunk Enterprise installation.

Install the S.o.S. Add-on on search-peers or forwarders to track resource usage.

By default, S.o.S. Add-on inputs are disabled. Enable the inputs to begin 
capturing resource usage information. 

NOTE: The data gathered by these inputs count against the daily licensed volume.

The 'sos' index must be enabled for S.o.S Add-on inputs to gather data. By 
default, the 'sos' index is enabled.


################################################################################
# To enable or disable data inputs
################################################################################

Enable the scripted inputs that collect information for the S.o.S. CPU/Memory
Usage and Distributed Searches Memory Usage views.


  From Splunk Web:
  1. Go to the Scripts page:

     (Splunk 4.3.x, Splunk 5.x) Manager > Data Inputs > Scripts
     (Splunk 6.0.x) Settings > Data Inputs > Scripts
  
  2. Enable the following scripted inputs:

      ps_sos.sh 
      lsof_sos.sh
   
  From a terminal window:

  Run the following commands from a terminal window:

    $SPLUNK_HOME/bin/splunk _internal call \
    '/servicesNS/nobody/TA-sos/data/inputs/script/.%252Fbin%252Fps_sos.sh' \
    -post:disabled 0
